data.content:
Your test works but uses generic `Assert.IsTrue` everywhere, which produces unhelpful failure messages like "Expected: True, Actual: False". MSTest 3.x+ has specialized collection assertions with much better diagnostics:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // "Assert.IsNotEmpty failed. Collection is empty."
    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);

    // "Assert.HasCount failed. Expected: 3, Actual: 2."
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);

    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));

    // "Assert.ContainsSingle failed. Collection contained 0 matching elements."
    Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Your code | Better alternative | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Clear "collection is empty" message |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Shows expected vs actual count |
| `Single()` + null check | `Assert.ContainsSingle(...)` | Better failure message, no exception on 0 or 2+ matches |

The `All(u => u.IsActive)` check has no built-in equivalent, so `Assert.IsTrue` is fine there — but consider adding a message parameter:

```csharp
Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Found inactive users in results");
```

These APIs require **MSTest 3.8+** (the `MSTest` metapackage or `MSTest.Sdk`).
